social_posts.post_text: Keep the North cold.
Like a faithful sled dog—sleeps outside, sure-footed, and loves to play in the snow.

“Isolation Camp, day 402. Winter has set in for good now. The brief spell of warmth a few weeks ago had the men out in shirtsleeves kicking an inflated penguin hide around on the ice. But today it is minus 14 and only the mechanics are out occasionally, running the diesel so it doesn’t freeze up. Peterson burned his hand badly when he attempted to thaw the oil sump using a Primus stove. He didn’t even feel the pain until one of his fingers was charred black. Doc Fuchs wanted to apply a poultice of oatmeal and a moldy piece of bread, but our food rations are precious so I told him to simply cut off the damaged finger. It went into the stew, though I didn’t tell the men. Nothing is wasted here...” - continued on my Substack.
Landy fettling friend.
Reporting for duty.
Keep warm. A full decade with the @bremontwatches Supermarine 2000. From ice diving in 2013 to hiking, skiing, and numerous tropical forays, it’s been a capable and inspiring companion.
Racing.

I was recently asked to contribute to the book, “A Life of Adventure” by the newly relaunched @jagojackets in the UK. I’m flattered to have been included alongside some pretty legendary adventurers like @levison.wood @davidyarrow @al_humphreys @bremontnick and others.

“Drink up, dreamers
You’re running dry.”
Urban explorations.
Giant stride into a new week.
Fifty fathoms and then some.
Dark mornings call for bright watches.
You’ve heard of secret fishing holes? Warmer days at a Midwestern cenote.
“Sometimes the old ways are best.”
Lean into it.
Backyard backcountry.
Cold Weather Operations.
Polar vortex.
The days can only get longer from now on.

Did you catch @submersiblewrist ‘s chat with @davehall1911 on @watchesofespionage this week? No self respecting dive watch devotee should skip that one. Big thanks to @submersiblewrist for the nerdiest holiday gift I’ve ever gotten—a Velcro dive strap with expanding buckle, the SEAL choice back in the day. Time to grow a mustache to match.

“The Year Adventure Returned.” 2022 was amazing: ice diving, jungle hikes, a month in Sri Lanka, Carolina mountains, Defender road trips, Caribbean reefcombing, winter frolicks, and I finished novel #2 (hopefully to be published in 2023 🤞🏻). I hope your year was rewarding and healthy. Time to shut down Instagram and enjoy the holidays. ✌🏻
Merry Christmas from Lac Perdu, where the snow is deep, the wind is cold, and the cider is hot.
For your eyes only.
Winter parking rules apply.

A piece of polar exploration history… the @yema_watches Bipole Duopoly, made to support the first full dogsled crossing of Antarctica by a team led by Will Steger and Jean-Louis Etienne in 1990. Titanium case, quartz movement suspended between two crystals for a reversible navigation instrument. The 24h hand can be used to navigate in both northern and southern hemispheres.
All-rounder.
Snow day.
Somewhere between Zermatt and Verbier, 2014.
Cozy, commando style.
It may have seemed wrong to test out the new Synchron Military Poseidon Ice Diver in the tropics but someone had to do it. Who doesn’t love a co-branded diver? And this one is especially sweet.

Another ice dive in the books. A frigid day for the 2023 North American Ice Diving Festival on White Bear Lake. Horrible viz, water temp a lot warmer than the air, and a lot of slogging for a few minutes of bottom time. But I’ll be back next year. Thanks to @joetron2030 @gishanir and @lattmudvigson (and Mom) for coming out to support. (📷: @gishanir and @lattmudvigson )

In the early 1950s, an intrepid group of divers in Duluth, Minnesota formed a club known, fittingly, as the Frigid Frogs. These adventurers set out along the north shore of Lake Superior to explore the wrecks of the numerous ships that met their fate, many during winter storms or collisions. They dove year round with early, crude diving gear—twin-hose regulators, single cylinders, and rubber dive suits, becoming the first to discover and document many of the significant wrecks in the region. Those of us who prize Great Lakes diving for its unique environs, challenges and pristine shipwrecks carry on their legacy, often exploring the same sites as those who first plumbed the depths. In order to honor the history of the Frigid Frogs, I decided to revive the name of this storied but little known club through a new logo, designed by @lattmudvigson . If you’re a Great Lakes diver and would like one of these stickers for your dive tank , shoot me a DM with some evidence of your own Great Lakes diving history (a photo, a story, a scanned logbook page). I’ll happily send one sticker to any honorary Frigid Frog if you send me a self-addressed stamped envelope (remember those?). Supplies are very limited! Stay chilly, my friends.
It takes a village… @lattmudvigson pours hot water on my frozen regulator post-dive, as I slowly succumb to rigor arctis. 📷: @gishanir
Is it summer yet?
Defrosting. 10 days ago, I was diving through a hole in the ice. Today it’s a hole in the floor. 📷: @gishanir
Not Minnesota.
Made some new friends today while diving the Tiputa Pass.

Happy Valentine’s Day from the middle of the Polynesian triangle. What a warm and welcoming place and rich culture born of the sea here. A special “māuruuru” to @blancpain1735 for making our visit incredibly memorable.
Old dog, new tricks. 📷: Etienne Menager
Stealth mode. 📷: E. Menager

When a mere 60 minutes aren’t enough. The new @blancpain1735 Fifty Fathoms Tech Gombessa is made for divers using closed circuit rebreathers that allow longer duration bottom times. A fourth running hand tracks dive time against the timing scale, up to three hours. I had a chance to try out the watch, and a rebreather, this week in Rangiroa, French Polynesia. It’s a remarkably simple solution to a real need, and one of the very few practical innovations on an analog dive watch in a long time.  It also wears incredibly well (even on Gishani’s small wrist). 📷: @gishanir (topside) and E. Menager (UW)
Into the blue. 📷: @gishanir
Making friends with the locals. Last week in French Polynesia.

“First having read the book of myths,
and loaded the camera,
and checked the edge of the knife-blade,
I put on
the body-armor of black rubber
the absurd flippers

I am having to do this
not like Cousteau with his
assiduous team

Milford Sound receives an average of 6 meters of rain per year. This creates a layer of freshwater on top of the salt, and a halocline down to 5 meters. It also means that black coral grows far shallower than usual, in massive “bushes.” Penguins, dolphins, seals, and giant octopus all flourish here. The views during surface intervals aren’t bad either.
Safety stop.
A lust for rust. 📷: @gishanir

70 years ago today, the first edition of “the spy story to end all spy stories” was published by Jonathan Cape in London, with a run of 4,728 books. Who could have imagined what would follow? 1953 was quite a year— the Rolex Submariner also debuted, Queen Elizabeth was crowned, and Everest was first summited.
How could I resist posting these again on the anniversary of the first 007 book’s publication? Goldeneye, birthplace of Bond.
Just say “no” to barotrauma.
I need a bigger garage.
Nautical vibes.
Royal flush.

“Sing me a song of a lad that is gone, 
Say, could that lad be I? 
Merry of soul he sailed on a day 
Over the sea to Skye.”
— R.L. Stevenson
The old man from Minnesota meets the Old Man of Storr. After a vigorous climb in proper Scottish weather we dropped in at Talisker for a smoky dram and then to the Oyster Shed for a cool dozen.

Not for the faint of heart. Rising, then dropping from sea level to 2,000 feet in just a few miles, with hairpin turns and some 20% grades, the Bealach na Ba (Applecross Pass) is a spectacular white knuckle drive, ending at Applecross Bay.
Waterfalls, wildlife, and whisky. Today we left the west coast behind and headed over to Golspie and Dornoch on the North Sea, via Wester Ross.

Visiting the Duke. With its 1,300-foot climb in a little over a mile, Ben Bhraggie really made us earn our pint.  The massive monument at the top pays tribute to a dubious character, the first Duke of Sutherland, who forcibly cleared people off the land in order to graze sheep. Regardless, it’s a lovely hike that starts right in Golspie town so you can finish at the pub.

social_posts.post_text: Dyed in the wool 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁳󠁣󠁴󠁿.

Tweed therapy. A drive through the Highlands would not be complete without a visit to @campbellsofbeauly a traditional purveyor of tweeds, tartans, and knitwear. Owner, John (with his lovely old Smiths W10 and Defender 90), took the time to show us around. It’s a shop I could have settled in with a cuppa and a good book and stayed all day. Instead I left with a couple of jumpers (that I’ll call “sweaters” once I’m back in the US).
Lochs and hillwalking at its finest in the Cairngorms. First up, a stroll to Loch Garten and Loch Mallachie, then a steep scramble up Sgòr Gaoithe.
“More than a piece of tarmac, it’s like a line in the landscape.” — @henrycatchpole . Taking the Old Military Road (A939) out of the highlands in spectacular fashion (and low gear).

Farewell to the Highlands, and to Scotland. It’s been a long-standing dream come true to drive a Land Rover around this magnificent country and it exceeded expectations. From challenging hikes to challenging roads, tweed to whisky, and all the people we met along the way, we fly home with the warmth of this place in our bellies like a peaty malt. The old Defender was a flawless steed, grunting up the climbs and handling the rough stuff with aplomb over ~500 miles. Though sad to see it come to an end, I know we’ll be back. Tìoraidh an-dràsta !

“For a student of diving history and exploration like me, the new Model 60 feels like a time capsule, pulled from a dusty dive locker in Hugh Edwards’s Perth basement. It makes me want to go diving—now!—far away, with a cadre of buddies, a small boat and maybe a speargun. We’ll catch our dinner on the reef and cook it over a driftwood fire on the beach, then suck down warm beer til long after the sun goes down. Then we’ll fall asleep under a tarp to the muted rumble of the compressor filling our cylinders for the next day, with dreams of cannons and bones, and capstans and dead-eyes, and maybe, if we’re lucky, an encrusted lump of silver coins.” — from my latest on Substack.

Working my way north, up Lake Michigan. Today was the Car Ferry Milwaukee, wrecked off the shore of its namesake city in 1929, taking all 52 crew members down. We dove the pilothouse and captain’s quarters, which blew off in the sinking and sits on the lake bed near the bow. We enjoyed stellar conditions if still a bit chilly at the bottom (42F = 6C). Amateur hour with the Super Professional.

A dive watch is pure adventure and derring-do. A chronograph—any chronograph—is, to me, the most interesting complication, pure function with a myriad of applications, and a true symbol of horological prowess. Combine these last two and you get something very special indeed, the watch nerd’s dive watch, bristling with potential energy and rugged capability. A dive chronograph demands to be used, challenges you to strap it on and go time new adventures—anywhere.

For those of us who grew up around the Great Lakes, November 10th is a sacred date. In 1975, the 729-foot freighter, Edmund Fitzgerald, sank in hurricane force winds and high seas on Lake Superior, taking all her 29 crew 530 feet deep to their untimely demise. The tragedy was immortalized in song and several books. The wreck is now an off limits gravesite, unseen since the 1990s when the bell was salvaged by a diver in a one-atmosphere Newtsuit. The wreck exists in my mind as the most cold, dark, and forbidding place.
Raise a dram to those who served and those who’ve been lost. Found this commemorative malt from @wolfburn_whisky at @carnegie_whisky_cellars in Scotland. Lest we forget.

I’m happy to announce that signed editions of my new novel, Sweetwater, are now available for purchase on my own website, jasonheatonauthor.com. It is, of course, also on Amazon and Apple Books, but without my illegible signature inside!

On this date, 1919. The Myron’s tale is a tragic one. A gale overwhelmed the underpowered steamer and soon the waves tore open her wooden hull. The crew of 17 made for the lifeboats, some slipping into the lake, others managing to board their tiny escape crafts. The captain valiantly remained in the pilothouse, intending to go down with his ship, but, ironically, he was its only survivor. As the ship surrendered to the waves, the pressure blew the pilothouse clear of the deck with the captain inside. He climbed onto the roof and floated for a full day before being rescued miles away. Some of the crew were found frozen in the lifeboat, dead, but others were missing until the following spring when eight bodies were found on shore, encased in ice. The corpses were unidentifiable and had to be chipped from the ice before all eight were buried in a pauper’s grave at a hilltop cemetery near Sault Saint Marie. (Photos by Chris Winters)
“I wanted a mission, and for my sins, they gave me one.”
Arctic Defender.

If the rumors are true, Phoenix has finally hung up the spring bars and closed shop. As one half of @thegreynato I observe a moment of silence for this longtime maker of tough military watch straps. There are a lot more players in the game now, but I still love the slightly stiff nylon and welded seams of the Phoenix G10 strap. And nobody did Admiralty Grey like they did. Smoke ‘em if you’ve got ‘em.

Nov. 29, 1905: November has always been a cruel month for sailors on Lake Superior, but November of 1905 was perhaps the worst since the big Lake was opened to navigation in 1855. 78 lives were lost and 19 ships sunk in storms that month, including the infamous “Mataafa Blow” which packed 60 mile per hour winds and sank a dozen ships. It was during this storm that the 436-foot steel schooner barge, Madeira, was driven against Gold Rock cliff on Superior’s rugged North Shore. Battered by short-frequency freshwater waves, Madeira quickly filled and sank, and her bones were scattered at the base of the cliff by ice and wave action over the ensuing decades. 

As the ship broke up, a brave crewman, Fred Benson, leaped to the cliff with a rope in hand and climbed up to the top. From there, he was able to throw a line down to the stricken vessel and all but the ship’s first mate were able to climb to safety. 

The Mataafa Blow and the wreck of the Madeira prompted the construction of Split Rock Lighthouse, which opened on an adjacent cliff five years later. The Madeira’s anchor is now displayed there. I’ve dived this wreck a dozen times over the years and it holds a special place for me. (📷 2,3: C Winters. The rest: @gishanir )

November 29, 1966. The SS Daniel J. Morrell, a 600-foot long steel freighter broke in half and sank in a fierce storm on Lake Huron. When the ship broke up, the bow sank immediately, while the stern end continued to steam on into the night, finally sinking five miles away. 28 of the 29 crew were lost, with the sole survivor, Dennis Hale, drifting for 36 hours in a lifeboat wearing only his underpants, a life jacket and his peacoat. The bow sits in about 170 feet of water. 📷: Chris Winters

“There’s no such thing as bad weather, just wrong wristwatch choices…” — Hans Wilsdorf (I think)

Choose wisely and get out there.
Finish the year strong.
May your axe always be sharp and your heart always warm.

2023 was one for the books—diving under the ice close to home, then in French Polynesia, Ecuador, Monterey, France, Florida, and my beloved Great Lakes, an epic trip to Scotland, and, oh yeah, I published my second novel. I post this not to boast or gloat, but hopefully to inspire others to pursue their dreams, take a few chances, stretch your limits a little. I know it was a difficult year for many. My 2024 will have a lot to live up to, but we’re not mere passengers of time, so make it your best year ever. See you on the other side.
No time like the present.
Winter’s only just begun.
